<subSubSection id="D8FB6574FFF9BD531F9CA89692670374" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CA89692670374" blockId="6.[178,1085,482,532]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Etymology: The specific epithet (Latin, noun in apposition) alludes to the swordshaped ventral process of the aedeagus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8FB6574FFF9BD531F9CAB5793210425" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" type="description">
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CAB57922603CB" blockId="6.[178,1085,547,683]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
Description: Body length 4.0- 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF9BD531D6BAB5792B20359" box="[581,663,547,569]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" unit="mm" value="4.9">4.9 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF9BD531C44AB5793C60359" box="[874,995,547,569]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" unit="mm" value="2.3" valueMax="2.4" valueMin="2.2">2.2-2.4 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531FDEAB4B911A0335" box="[240,319,575,597]" captionStart="Figs 10-17" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[182,1083,212,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 10-17: Orsunius stimulans nov.sp. (10-13) and O. gladiator nov.sp. (14-17): (10, 14) habitus; (11, 15) forebody; (12, 16) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) aedeagus in ventral view; (17) ventral process in ventral view. Scale bars: 10-11, 14-15: 1.0 mm; 12-13, 16-17: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305065/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
. Coloration: head dark-reddish; pronotum bright-reddish; elytra reddishbrown with the posterior two-fifths and the humeral angles reddish-yellow; abdomen brown, with the posterior portion of segment VII and all of segment VIII dark-yellowish; legs yellowish; antennae reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CABCD93A702F7" blockId="6.[178,1086,697,919]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
Head (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531FD9ABCD916703AF" box="[247,322,697,719]" captionStart="Figs 10-17" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[182,1083,212,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 10-17: Orsunius stimulans nov.sp. (10-13) and O. gladiator nov.sp. (14-17): (10, 14) habitus; (11, 15) forebody; (12, 16) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) aedeagus in ventral view; (17) ventral process in ventral view. Scale bars: 10-11, 14-15: 1.0 mm; 12-13, 16-17: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305065/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) strongly transverse, approximately 1.25 times as broad as long, broadest across eyes, weakly tapering behind eyes, and with sharply marked posterior angles; posterior margin very weakly concave in the middle; punctation moderately dense and very coarse, median dorsal portion with a subcircular impunctate patch; interstices without microsculpture; lateral margins with long black setae (broken off in 
<typeStatus id="4F5A885DFFF9BD531CB3AA5F93DF0221" box="[925,1018,811,833]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">holotype</typeStatus>
). Eyes large and strongly bulging, somewhat longer than postocular portion in dorsal view. Antennae 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF9BD531E32AA109149021A" box="[284,364,868,890]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
long and slender; preapical antennomeres approximately as broad as long. Anterior margin of labrum with V-shaped excision in the middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CAAD293B90571" blockId="6.[178,1085,933,1041]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531E0BAAD1915502DB" box="[293,368,933,955]" captionStart="Figs 10-17" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[182,1083,212,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 10-17: Orsunius stimulans nov.sp. (10-13) and O. gladiator nov.sp. (14-17): (10, 14) habitus; (11, 15) forebody; (12, 16) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) aedeagus in ventral view; (17) ventral process in ventral view. Scale bars: 10-11, 14-15: 1.0 mm; 12-13, 16-17: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305065/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) 1.15 times as wide as long and slightly broader than head; posterior angles rounded, weakly marked; lateral margins with long black setae (broken off in 
<typeStatus id="4F5A885DFFF9BD531F9CAAAA912A0294" box="[178,271,990,1012]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">holotype</typeStatus>
); punctation moderately dense and coarse, but slightly less so than that of head; midline with narrow impunctate band; interstices without microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CAD6B919105EA" blockId="6.[178,1085,1055,1163]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531E2CAD6B916A0555" box="[258,335,1055,1077]" captionStart="Figs 10-17" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[182,1083,212,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 10-17: Orsunius stimulans nov.sp. (10-13) and O. gladiator nov.sp. (14-17): (10, 14) habitus; (11, 15) forebody; (12, 16) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) aedeagus in ventral view; (17) ventral process in ventral view. Scale bars: 10-11, 14-15: 1.0 mm; 12-13, 16-17: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305065/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as pronotum; punctation dense and fine; interstices without microsculpture. Hind wings fully developed. Protarsomeres I-IV distinctly dilated. Metatarsomere I moderately slender, longer than II, but shorter than the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CADED93D805AB" blockId="6.[178,1086,1177,1227]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Abdomen slightly narrower than elytra; punctation dense and extremely fine; interstices with distinct microreticulation; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531FE9ADAF93210425" blockId="6.[178,1086,1242,1349]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
: sternite VII with weakly concave posterior margin; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531CBBADAE93F00590" box="[917,981,1242,1264]" captionStart="Figs 1-9" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1420,1440]" captionTargetBox="[186,1058,212,1392]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1063,212,1409]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-9: Orsunius spathulatus nov.sp. (1-6), O. stimulans nov.sp. (7-8), and O. gladiator nov.sp. (9): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3, 8, 9) male sternite VIII; (4) posterior portion of male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in lateral view; (6) ventral process in ventral view; (7) male sternite VII. Scale bars: 1- 2: 1.0 mm; 3-9: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305063/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.05 times as long as broad and with barely noticeable, extremely shallow and broad posterior excision; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531D1AAC67928C0449" box="[564,681,1299,1321]" captionStart="Figs 10-17" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1516,1536]" captionTargetBox="[182,1083,212,1491]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1091,212,1505]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 10-17: Orsunius stimulans nov.sp. (10-13) and O. gladiator nov.sp. (14-17): (10, 14) habitus; (11, 15) forebody; (12, 16) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) aedeagus in ventral view; (17) ventral process in ventral view. Scale bars: 10-11, 14-15: 1.0 mm; 12-13, 16-17: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305065/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Figs 16-17</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF9BD531D92AC67933E0449" box="[700,795,1299,1321]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" unit="mm" value="0.73">0.73 mm</quantity>
long, ventral process conspicuously long and slender, sword-shaped in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8FB6574FFF9BD531F9CAC20940C04C3" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CAC20940C04C3" blockId="6.[178,1085,1364,1443]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
Comparative notes: In size, coloration, and habitus, 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF9BD531C7DAC2193F5040A" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[851,976,1364,1386]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gladiator">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF9BD531C7DAC2193F5040A" box="[851,976,1364,1386]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">O. gladiator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
somewhat resembles 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF9BD531E33AC05915C04E6" baseAuthorityName="BERNHAUER" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[285,377,1393,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="immsi">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF9BD531E33AC05915C04E6" box="[285,377,1393,1414]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">O. immsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it is distinguished by the distinctly coarser punctation of the more transverse head, as well as by the completely different male sexual characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8FB6574FFF9BD531F9CACC591A60759" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="905E36FFFFF9BD531F9CACC591A60759" blockId="6.[178,1085,1457,1593]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">
Distribution and natural history: The species is known from two localities in northern and southern 
<collectingCountry id="E8F6766FFFF9BD531D63ACBA92820484" box="[589,679,1486,1508]" name="Thailand" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="08DA2A7AFFF9BD531D99ACBA92DB0484" box="[695,766,1486,1508]" captionStart="Map 2" captionStartId="2.[178,223,1075,1095]" captionTargetBox="[178,1092,212,1064]" captionTargetId="figure-2@2.[178,1092,212,1064]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Map 2: Distributions of Orsunius gladiator (white and black circles), O. latexcisus (black circle), O. flavovirgatus (black circle), O. heissi (black star), O. stimulans (black and grey triangles), O. granulosus (white and grey triangles), O. cuneatus (white diamond), and O. spathulatus (black square)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305061/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">Map 2</figureCitation>
). The slightly teneral 
<typeStatus id="4F5A885DFFF9BD531CC8ACBB94180484" box="[998,1085,1487,1508]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">paratype</typeStatus>
was collected on a river bank with sand and stones at an altitude of 
<quantity id="57199B1AFFF9BD531CBDAC9E942D0760" box="[915,1032,1514,1536]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" unit="m" value="450.0" valueMax="550.0" valueMin="350.0">
350- 
<specimenCount id="86E7FD76FFF9BD531CEFAC9E942D0760" box="[961,1032,1514,1536]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" type="generic">550 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. The 
<typeStatus id="4F5A885DFFF9BD531F9CAF73912E077D" box="[178,267,1543,1565]" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected together with 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF9BD531D12AF7C92E7077D" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[572,706,1543,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latexcisus">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF9BD531D12AF7C92E7077D" box="[572,706,1543,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">O. latexcisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF9BD531DFCAF7C9315077D" baseAuthorityName="BERNHAUER" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[722,816,1544,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="immsi">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF9BD531DFCAF7C9315077D" box="[722,816,1544,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">O. immsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="57E14D7CFFF9BD531C6EAF7C93C2077D" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[832,999,1543,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Orsunius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="467" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavovirgatus">
<emphasis id="A295EAEDFFF9BD531C6EAF7C93C2077D" box="[832,999,1543,1565]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="467">O. flavovirgatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and an undescribed species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
